<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JAN 92 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow subdued ahead of State of
Union address
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
SHARE prices were becalmed in light trading yesterday, as investors remained
on the sidelines ahead of today's important State of the Union address to
Congress by President George Bush, writes Patrick Harverson in New York.
At the close the Dow Jones Industrial Average was up 7.83 at 3,240.61,
having spent the day only a few points above Friday's finish. The more
broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 ended 0.50 down at 414.98, while the
Nasdaq composite of over-the-counter stocks lost 3.68 to 621.00.
Turnover on the New York SE amounted to 191m shares, while rises outscored
falls by a narrow margin.
After last week's declines, the market opened in a subdued mood yesterday.
All eyes were fixed on the US president's State of the Union speech,
scheduled for 8pm New York time this evening.
Mr Bush is expected to unveil a package of tax cuts aimed at stimulating the
sluggish economy. Although tax cuts should be generally positive for the
stock markets, there is concern that any measures would lead to a widening
in the budget deficit, which could prompt a sharp rise in bond yields.
Diversified securities house Merrill Lynch shed Dollars 2 1/2 to Dollars 61
1/8 in spite of record full-year earnings of Dollars 696m, achieved with the
help of a Dollars 171m fourth-quarter profit.
The record figures had been expected in the wake of buoyant securities
markets in the final quarter, and the decline in the price yester-day was
put down to profit-taking following the stock's strong performance over the
past 52 weeks.
LA Gear slipped Dollars  3/4 to Dollars 15 1/2 after the company formally
announced the retirement of Mr Robert Greenberg, its founder, from the posts
of chairman and chief executive. The sports-shoe maker will unveil a new
marketing campaign this week. Of its rivals, Nike eased Dollars  1/2 to
Dollars 72 1/2 and Reebok International relinquished Dollars  5/8 to Dollars
30 1/2 .
Chrysler enjoyed a rare gain, advancing Dollars 1 1/2 to Dollars 15 on the
back of a reported upgrading from Shearson Lehman, the broking house. The
remaining members of the Big Three car manufacturers also firmed, with
General Motors adding Dollars 1 3/8 at Dollars 34 1/8 and Ford rising
Dollars  1/2 to Dollars 32 3/4 .
On the over-the-counter market, Hutchinson Technology climbed Dollars 1 1/2
to Dollars 24 3/4 after reporting net income of 54 cents a share for the
first fiscal quarter, well up on the 35 cents a share earned at the same
stage a year ago.
Going the other way on the earnings front was Arkansas Freightways, which
tumbled Dollars 3 1/4 to Dollars 32 1/2 on news of a fourth-quarter profit
of 20 cents a share, down from the 33 cents earned a year earlier.
Canada
TORONTO stocks, after a firm opening, fell back to close with an easier bias
on balance after moderate trading. A weak Canadian dollar, however, helped
some resource-based issues to improve.
The composite index was finally 2.2 off at 3,628.5, while declining issues
outnumbered advances by 308 to 267. Volume decreased to 23.3m shares from
Friday's 28m. The index was ahead almost 15 points in the first half-hour of
trading, but quickly settled back and then traded in a narrow range for the
rest of the day.
Du Pont Canada 'A' dipped CDollars  1/2 to CDollars 41 1/4 . The company
reported fourth-quarter earnings of CDollars 14.3m, or 46 cents a share, up
from CDollars 10.3m, or 33 cents, a year earlier.
</TEXT>
