<DATE>920128
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JAN 92 / International Company News: Macy's files for protection
under Chapter 11
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
R. H. Macy, one of America's largest department store chains, yesterday
filed for protection against its creditors under Chapter 11 of the US
bankruptcy code - the latest, and one of the largest, casualties of the
leveraged buy-out mania of the 1980s.
The company, which has one of the world's best retailing franchises, was
taken private by its management in a Dollars 3.6bn buy-out in 1986, but it
has struggled for years with a heavy debt burden, currently estimated at
around Dollars 3.7bn.
Recession in the US and poor sales during the crucial Christmas season
delivered the final blow, reducing cashflow to the point where it could not
pay its suppliers, who began to hold back merchandise shipments.
Mr Edward Finkelstein, the chairman, who just weeks ago denied that a
Chapter 11 filing was an option, said: 'We worked day and night to find a
suitable solution, and ultimately came to the conclusion that filing for
Chapter 11 was best for Macy's future. I am convinced that beginning this
rehabilitative process is the best way to protect our valuable franchise.'
Macy's is expected to follow the path of other retailing groups which have
gone through Chapter 11 bankruptcy, reorganised their finances, and emerged
essentially intact, albeit somewhat smaller, with control of the group
handed over to senior creditors in return for debt relief.
Before filing for Chapter 11, Macy's yesterday obtained a vital Dollars 600m
debtor-in-possession financing commitment from Chemical Banking and Bankers
Trust. These funds, which have priority in any debt repayment, will allow
the company to meet the day-to-day financing needs of the business,
including employee salaries and payment to suppliers.
All Macy's 144 stores remained open yesterday and operating as usual. The
company has 98 outlets using the Macy's name, mainly in the north-east US,
the south and California. It also operates 29 Bullock's and 24 I. Magnin
stores in California. The company bought the latter two chains in a
misjudged acquisition in 1988 which added Dollars 1bn to its already heavy
debt burden.
Among the main losers from yesterday's filing will be the holders of Macy's
equity, including its management; GE Capital, the financial services arm of
the General Electric group; and Loews Corporation, the diversified company
headed by Mr Laurence Tisch. A Dollars 1bn eleventh hour rescue attempt by
Mr Tisch broke down on Friday night, prompting yesterday's bankruptcy
filing.
Other losers will include the holders of Macy's unsecured junk bonds, issued
at the time of the buy-out, who will get back only a fraction of their
investment.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
