<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JAN 92 / International Company News: Union Carbide suffers Dollars
28m loss
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN FRIEDMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A SPIKE in raw material prices plus Dollars 220m of special charges
associated with a restructuring programme caused Union Carbide, the big US
chemicals company, to suffer a Dollars 28m loss in 1991, compared with a
Dollars 308m net profit in 1990.
The company took a Dollars 70m pre-tax (Dollars 46m after-tax)
fourth-quarter special charge. This was for severance payments and facility
consolidation costs associated with its previously announced restructuring.
Costs associated with the proposed spin-off of its industrial gases business
were also part of the special charge.
Union Carbide suffered a Dollars 63m loss in the fourth quarter of 1991,
compared with a Dollars 7m net profit in the last quarter of 1990.
Fourth-quarter sales, restated to reflect the not-yet-completed spin-off of
the industrial gases business, were 14.6 per cent lower at Dollars 1.15bn.
For the whole of 1991, on the same basis, sales were 7 per cent down at
Dollars 4.88bn.
Last September, Union Carbide said it would cut its workforce by 5,500 as
part of a cost-cutting programme that aims to reduce annual expenses by
Dollars 250m by 1994.
First-quarter earnings were reduced by the serious disruption caused by an
explosion that killed several workers last March at a chemicals plant in
Seadrift, Texas.
Mr Robert Kennedy, Union Carbide's chairman, said the company had
accelerated its cost-cutting. He said the fourth-quarter results, even
excluding the special charges, reflected very competitive market conditions
and a spike in raw material prices - especially for polyethylene and
ethylene glycol - that reduced profit margins.
On Wall Street, Union Carbide's share price closed at Dollars 24, down
Dollars  3/8 .
</TEXT>
