FT  28 JAN 92 / International Company News: Total sees 41% climb in net
earnings
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM DAWKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
TOTAL, the French state-controlled oil group, yesterday estimated net
earnings rose by 41 per cent last year to FFr5.8bn (Dollars 1.07bn).
The increase, from FFr4.1bn in 1990, represents a slowdown on the growth
published in the previous year. However, Total has since changed its
accounting methods to reduce the wild swings in its results that used to
come from oil price changes. It has switched from accounting for stocks on a
first in, first out basis to accounting for oil stocks at replacement cost.
Last year's growth reflects an upturn in activity and productivity gains
across the group, said Total. Margins were lifted by the Gulf war, but then
shrank with the subsequent fall in oil prices and the dollar's value.
Total's oil and gas reserves outside the Middle East rose by more than 15
per cent, while sales of crude oil rose by 13 per cent, faster than the
market,
</TEXT>
