</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JAN 92 / Four Maxwell pension funds to close
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FOUR MAXWELL pensions funds, covering about 4,000 people are to be wound up.
They are the first to be closed since the collapse of the Maxwell empire.
The decision was taken by Mr Alan Fishman, of Clay &amp; Partners Pension
Trustees, because of the large sums of money missing from the funds and
because 'the chances of them being made up are negligible'.
The funds involved are for employees and management at AGB Research, the
market research group, which was bought by Mr Robert Maxwell's private
interests, and the employees of his cable television interests.
Winding up will take some time and Mr Fishman said the trustees would
'ensure, as far as we are able, that benefits continue to be paid'. It was
clear last night however that many of the employees are likely to lose the
money they have paid into the funds.
There is little chance of any money for deferred pensioners, who left the
company but still had some pensions rights, or those currently employed by
the companies involved. The position is unclear what priorities there will
be for block transfers, groups of employees who have moved in or out of the
schemes as a result of purchases or disposals in the Maxwell empire.
Present pensioners have the first priority and continue to receive their
pensions. However the value of their ultimate pensions will depend on the
financial state of the funds when the windings up are complete and all
assets realised.
Mr Fishman declined to discuss numbers last night but it is clear there may
not be enough for all pensioners to receive their full entitlements. The
funds being wound up are the AGB Research Group Retirement Benefits Scheme,
the AGB Pension Scheme, the Maxwell Media Pensions Plan (covering cable) and
the Directors Pension Plan.
Mr Fishman said last night it had been his duty to make a ruling on the four
funds. He had decided to end the speculation and uncertainty although
inevitably there were human tragedies involved.
A member of the consultative committee on the MCC pension fund said: 'In the
absence of any recovery of money missing from the MCC pension fund what has
happened at AGB must be a matter of great concern for members of the MCC
fund.'
</TEXT>
