<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JAN 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Coming rather late to the Falklands War Replay Stakes, ITV begins a
documentary series, In Time Of War (7.30), which, surprise surprise, begins
with Governor Rex Hunt warning the islanders that they are about to be
invaded. The standard of chairman on Assignment's occasional discussion
programmes is being maintained: the excellent John Tusa is going (it was
surprising that the managing director of the World Service ever did find the
time) but is being replaced by the estimable Sheena McDonald. In her first
programme (7.45 BBC2) the subject is the United Nations.
At 8.00, Channel 4 shows the first of a six-part series, Class Action, on
what we are are assured is a crisis in British education (when was there no
'crisis'?). In Without Walls (9.00 C4) novelist Saul Bellow has the first of
five conversations 'exploring people's growing sense of unease as the world
moves towards the year 2000'. Since the calendar is an artificial man-made
concept it will be interesting to see what the fuss is about.
BBC1's Inside Story Special (10.25) promises 'a dramatic new perspective' on
Londonderry's 'Bloody Sunday' which occurred 20 years ago.
</TEXT>
