<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JAN 92 / Parliament and Politics: Legislation pledge on computer
evidence - Poll Tax
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LEGISLATION to end the uncertainty about the use of computer evidence in
poll tax cases was promised yesterday by the government as an amendment to
the Council Tax Bill.
The move was immediately condemned by Labour as too slow, while some local
authority associations warned of difficulties for councils over enforcing
liability orders before the new law takes effect, probably early in March.
Mr Michael Heseltine, the environment secretary, said the amendment would
put beyond doubt councils' ability to present computer evidence in
magistrates court applications for liability orders to cover enforcement of
the poll tax, the business rate and the council tax.
The Council Tax Bill is currently receiving detailed debate in the Lords.
The government could not say yesterday when the amendment would be brought
forward, but it will have to be during the next few weeks.
The proposed change will not apply to the use of computer evidence in other
cases. Ministers are still considering the more general question of hearsay
evidence, but the decision to act on poll tax cases alone prompted
speculation of continuing differences between the Department of the
Environment and the Home Office.
Mr Bryan Gould, shadow environment secretary, said the government should
have taken stronger action and made the change retrospective. He warned that
the delay in clarifying the law would mean higher bills next year, because
councils would be unable to enforce the poll tax until the change became
law.
The Environment Department said, however, that there was no case for
compensating councils because even where they decided to suspend proceedings
until after the change in the law, they would suffer only the loss of
interest on their cashflow.
The announcement came against a backdrop of heightened political wrangling
about poll tax bills due to be sent out in March. Mr Gould, accusing
ministers of being 'in a panic' about the bills, said he would not be
surprised at some minor change to the poll tax in the Budget in order to
delay distribution of bills until after the general election.
Mr Heseltine promised last week that there would be no tax. Ministers have
acknowledged that poll tax bills were likely to overshoot government
predictions by up to Pounds 15, but reject Labour claims that the target
poll tax figure of Pounds 257 - if councils spent according to government
assessments of what they needed - would in practice end up closer to Pounds
300.
</TEXT>
