<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JAN 92 / Parliament and Politics: Tories plan to extend private
prisons - Home Affairs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CATHERINE MILTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Conservative election manifesto will commit the government to extending
its programme of prison privatisation, Mrs Angela Rumbold, Home Office
minister, said yesterday.
Britain's first privately managed prison, the Wolds remand prison at
Everthorpe, Humberside, is due to open in April, while a tender competition
has been announced for Blakenhurst local prison near Redditch, Hereford and
Worcester.
In an interview with the Financial Times, Mrs Rumbold said: 'The difficulty
with Wolds is that it was built by the prison service. The ideal is really
to say to a firm we will give you the opportunity to develop this new prison
and it is a contract to design, build and manage.
'That is always an infinitely better prospect because they don't have to
take on some of the possible built-in inefficiencies of somebody else's
design.'
The government had made no secret of the fact that if contracting-out tests
were successful, 'we shall continue to go out to tender for as long as there
are people willing to undertake this work'.
Mrs Rumbold said while the new Criminal Justice Act gave ministers powers to
extend privatisation to all except high security prisons they would proceed
slowly. 'It may be that the whole venture at the end of the day is not a
particularly successful idea, in which case I don't want to box myself in.'
Mrs Rumbold, a member of the Thatcherite No Turning Back Group, has
expressed concern that private and public sectors might not fit together,
and has said she did not want to provoke prison staff.
Yesterday she admitted she remained cautious. 'I don't want to foist an idea
on to the system without having sufficient caution to say that I am not
going to go headlong down that route. I am going to take it step by step so
that we can test it properly.'
</TEXT>
