<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JAN 92 / UK News (Employment): Rolls-Royce cuts pay increase for car
workers as sales fall
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS and MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ROLLS-ROYCE Motor Cars is to halve cost-of-living pay increases for its
3,000-strong workforce because of the continued fall in worldwide sales.
Workers had expected a 6 per cent pay rise in February, plus 4 per cent in
return for the introduction of new working practices. The 4 per cent will
still be paid but there will be only 3 per cent extra as a cost-of-living
increase.
The increases had been agreed with unions under a two-year deal; the second
year of the agreement begins next month. The reduced increase has been
approved by unions.
Two-year deals are common in motor manufacturing as a way of increasing
stability and reducing time spent on pay talks. It is extremely unusual for
the second part of a two-year agreement to be renegotiated, even if there is
a drop in prevailing rates of pay or inflation slows.
The Engineering Employers' Federation said last week that the median among
its affiliates concluding pay deals in December was 4 per cent.
Ford recently concluded a two-year pay deal for its 29,000 manual workers
that led to pay rises of 5 per cent.
Vauxhall, in pay negotiations covering 9,000 manual workers, has offered 5
per cent in the first year, again as part of a two-year deal.
Rolls-Royce said that in view of market conditions it would have been
'madness' to pay increases of the size previously agreed under the two-year
deal. Had the agreement not been in place, the workforce would not have
expected any pay increase, it added.
The company, which is a subsidiary of Vickers, cut its workforce by more
than a third last year and introduced three-day working at one of its
plants.
Sales worldwide dropped by about half last year compared with 1990.
Recessions in the UK and the US have hit sales.
The introduction of a US luxury car tax has also had a strong impact on
sales of the company's Rolls-Royce and Bentley cars. It said yesterday that
it could see no immediate uplift in business.
</TEXT>
