<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JAN 92 / Pensions fund code issued
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THE NATIONAL Association of Pension Funds yesterday unveiled a code of
practice designed to prevent fund management groups from selling their
services based on misleading presentations of their performance records.
The code, intended to be voluntary, follows an association study which
concluded that fund managers competing for business presented information
about their success that made comparisons difficult.
Mr David Adams of the British Rail Pension Trust Company, who chairs the
NAPF committee which drafted the code, said: 'People naturally wanted to
advertise their best points for commercially valid reasons.' The code
applies to all unsolicited advertisements received by pension fund trustees
and is intended to take effect immediately.
</TEXT>
