<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JAN 92 / Inquiry opens today into proposed Pounds 25m bridge to Skye
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE CONTROVERSIAL plan to build a privately funded toll bridge over the sea
to the isle of Skye, off the west highlands of Scotland is to be tested at a
public inquiry starting today.
Many local people reject the principle of a toll bridge on a route that has
no easy alternative. They oppose the formula for setting tolls in line with
the ferry charge of Pounds 4.20 for a car, with a 50 per cent discount for
locals. By comparison, the toll for a car on the Forth road bridge is 40p.
Others object to the design of the concrete box-girder bridge. Some oppose
the construction of a bridge altogether and would prefer to keep the
Caledonian MacBrayne ferries, which began operating a 24-hour service last
year.
Last month the Scottish Office signed contracts with a joint venture of
Miller Group, the Edinburgh-based construction company, and Dywidag of
Germany.
The consortium will build the bridge and have a concession to charge tolls
for up to 27 years, although the bridge is expected to pay for itself in
about 15 years.
The bridge will cost about Pounds 25m, of which Pounds 8m will be paid by
the Scottish Office for the approach roads. It will be the first privately
financed toll bridge in Scotland. In England, Trafalgar House operates a
toll bridge across the Thames at Dartford and an Anglo-French consortium is
building one across the Severn.
The inquiry, which is to be held in Kyle of Lochalsh on the mainland side of
the crossing, will consider nearly 200 objections and may take three weeks.
There are no objections from people or institutions directly affected by the
project.
Miss Elizabeth Haran, the Scottish Office reporter (inspector) at the
inquiry, might in theory recommend against the plan for the bridge. However,
the contractors hope to start work in April for completion in early 1995.
Many of the 9,000 people on Skye want a bridge, believing it will benefit
the island's tourist industry and reduce the sense of isolation resulting
from being linked to the mainland only by the ferry. The crossing takes four
minutes.
However, a minority of the inhabitants, including many who have moved to the
island from England, believe that extra tourists will ruin the island, and
want to preserve its separateness from the mainland.
Recently the National Trust for Scotland, which owns part of the land that
the bridge and its approach roads will cross, agreed modifications to the
bridge with the Scottish Office, which will add Pounds 1.3m to its cost.
Some Trust officials had favoured a more spectacular but expensive bridge of
the cable-stay type for this beauty spot, but that objection was dropped.
In spite of the opposition to the high tolls, the government says that a
publicly funded bridge could not be justified for 25 years.
</TEXT>
