<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JAN 92 / New charter airline to fly A320s
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS, Aerospace Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE LAUNCH of a UK charter airline yesterday gave the European Airbus
consortium a psychological boost as the new carrier announced that it would
start operations in May with three A320 airliners.
The highly computerised twin-engine aircraft has been at the centre of
controversy after the crash of an Air Inter A320 in France last week in
which 87 people died.
But Mr Bob O'Donnell, the managing director of the new charter airline,
Excalibur Airways, said he had no doubts about the integrity of the A320's
systems. In two previous crashes the aircraft, its systems and engines had
been cleared, and Mr O'Donnell said he expected the aircraft to be
exonerated again in France.
The airline is the first UK charter carrier to operate the A320 on charter
services. British Airways operates 10 A320s on scheduled routes.
Investigators are trying to discover the cause of last week's A320 crash,
but the French civil aviation authority said an initial examination of the
aircraft's flight recorders had yielded no reason to ground other A320s.
The new airline has been constituted after a management buy-out of Trans
Europe Airways UK, the British charter subsidiary of the collapsed TEA
Belgian airline.
TEA, one of the victims of the decline in air travel caused by the Gulf war
and the economic slowdown, went into bankruptcy last year. Although its UK
subsidiary was profitable, it was forced to suspend operations last
September after the demise of its Belgian parent company.
The new airline is the second UK carrier to have been reconstituted from the
collapse of previous airlines. The other is Euroworld Airways, the
Gatwick-based commuter airline, part of the failed Air Europe group. It
started operations again under new management last year and renamed itself
Cityflyer Express last week.
The management of the former TEA UK charter airline has been backed in its
buy-out by 3i, the investment capital group, and Air Malta. Both 3i and the
Maltese national airline are taking a 30 per cent stake each in Excalibur
Airways, with the former TEA UK management team taking the remaining 40 per
cent.
Mr Albert Mizzi, Air Malta's chairman, said yesterday his airline had been
seeking to invest in another carrier.
Excalibur Airways is to start operations in May with two A320s based at
London Gatwick and one at Manchester international airport. The airline,
whose headquarters is East Midlands international airport, expects to carry
half a million passengers in its first 12 months and is planning to expand
its fleet next year.
Excalibur is leasing the three A320s from GPA, the Irish aircraft leasing
group. The three aircraft are together worth about Pounds 85m.
Master of good timing, Page 25
</TEXT>
