FT  28 JAN 92 / Cameroon's debts rescheduled
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By AP
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Creditor nations working through the Paris Club rescheduled the official
foreign debt of Cameroon over 15 to 20 years yesterday, AP reports from
Paris.
The creditors announced that they advised stretching debt service payments
to 20 years for public development assistance loans, and 15 years for other
types of guaranteed loans. They did not say what amount of debt was covered
by the package, but urged other creditors to arrange debt conversions for
Cameroon.
Those participating in the Cameroon talks included Austria, Belgium,
Britain, Canada, Denmark, France, Germany, Italy, Japan, the Netherlands,
Sweden, Switzerland, and the US.
