FT  28 JAN 92 / Israeli PM survives confidence motions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE minority government of the Israeli prime minister, Mr Yitzhak Shamir,
survived five parliamentary motions of no confidence yesterday, Reuter
reports.
The motions were put down in a single vote which resulted in a 55-49 victory
for the government with five abstentions, a Knesset (parliament) spokesman
said.
It was the first challenge to Mr Shamir's fragile coalition since two
far-right parties pulled out last week over participation in Middle East
peace talks.
Opposition parties brought the motions in protest at what they described as
deteriorating social and economic conditions in Israel - rising unemployment
coupled with lavish spending on construction of Jewish settlements in the
occupied territories.
Mr Shamir's success in mustering enough support for his government in the
vote will give him the upper hand in setting the early date for national
elections set for November but now expected to take place within six months.
Senior members of Mr Shamir's Likud party yesterday began consultations with
coalition partners and opposition parties on the election date.
