<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JAN 92 / Record exports boost hopes for economic revival: Stronger
pound increases speculation over interest rate cut ahead of Budget
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE British government was yesterday given fresh heart on the economy with
news of record exports in the final quarter of last year.
Indications that UK exporters are continuing to find sales opportunities in
a fragile world economy helped sentiment on the London stock market, where
shares ended firmly higher.
A strengthening of sterling against a weak D-Mark also in-creased
speculation that Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, might find room to cut
in-terest rates before the Budget on March 10 in a move which would help the
government's general election chances.
The developments gave Mr Lamont, who in recent weeks has been troubled by a
weak pound and signs of continuing deep recession, his most heartening day
on the economic front since Christmas.
According to the Central Statistical Office, export volumes in the three
months to December were up 0.5 per cent compared with the previous quarter,
and 3 per cent higher than in the same period in 1990.
Last month, exports grew in value by 2 1/2 per cent compared with November
to Pounds 9bn, while imports stayed little changed at Pounds 9.6bn.
According to the CSO, the total deficit on the current account last month
came out at Pounds 388m, as against expectations in the City of a Pounds
500m deficit. In November, the figure was Pounds 630m.
The figures helped to buoy the stock market, where the FT-SE 100 index of
leading shares closed below the day's highs at 2,539.9, up 29.5. On currency
markets, the pound climbed three-quarters of a pfennig against the D-Mark,
closing in London at DM2.8725. In New York yesterday evening it was slightly
up at DM2.8737.
Sterling remains only about a  1/2 pfennig above its theoretical floor in
the European exchange rate mechanism (ERM) against the peseta, the strongest
currency in the system. But it is far enough away from its D-Mark 'lower
floor' of DM2.78 for the government soon to start contemplating the
possibility of a reduction in base rates. These have been stuck at 10.5 per
cent for nearly five months, during which many politicians and
industrialists have called for new cuts in borrowing costs to aid the
recovery.
The good performance by UK exporters during 1991 was a big factor behind a
fall in the current-account deficit for the whole of 1991 to Pounds 5.8bn,
from Pounds 15.2bn in 1990. In the government's Autumn Statement in
November, Mr Lamont had predicted a deficit of Pounds 6.5bn. Also
contributing to the cut in the overall deficit was a sharp drop in imports,
caused by low demand due to the recession. Although the CSO said import
volumes between the third and fourth quarters of 1991 were virtually flat -
providing little evidence that faint stirrings of recovery were stoking
increased demand for imports - yesterday's figures encouraged hopes that
good export growth during 1992 will aid the UK economy.
Despite signs of a puncturing of the general gloom about the economy over
the past month, many investors remain cautious about the short-term outlook.
Today's quarterly report on industrial trends by the Confederation of
British Industry is expected to paint a downbeat picture of prospects over
the next few months.
While the Treasury said the export figures were 'quite en-couraging', the
government's political opponents took the chance to highlight the size of
the trade deficit, which Labour and the Liberal Democrats took as a measure
of underlying economic weakness.
Mr Gordon Brown, the shadow trade and industry secretary, said Britain was
still firmly stuck in recession, while the Liberal Democrats said: 'An
end-of-year deficit of (nearly) Pounds 6bn during the deepest recession
Britain has experienced since the war is disgraceful.'
Trade deficit smallest for eight years Page 8 Lex Page 18 Currencies Page 29
</TEXT>
