<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JAN 92 / International Company News: Merrill Lynch unveils record
full-year earnings of Dollars 696m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
AN OUTSTANDING 1991 for Wall Street was sealed yesterday when the biggest US
securities house, Merrill Lynch, unveiled full-year profits of Dollars
696.1m, the highest in the company's history. In 1990, profits totalled
Dollars 191.9m.
Merrill's record performance was achieved in the wake of a spectacular
fourth quarter, when earnings raced up 463 per cent to Dollars 170.7m on the
back of buoyant stock markets and heavy equity and bond underwriting
activity.
The improvement in revenues during the final quarter from all the company's
businesses was mirrored in the full-year figures. The steady fall in
interest rates over the year attracted many investors back to the stock
market and, as a result, revenues from commissions over the year jumped 22
per cent to Dollars 2.1bn. In the last quarter, commissions rose 36 per cent
to Dollars 556.1m.
Earnings from principal transactions also soared in the wake of lower
interest rates, a trend which favours broking houses with a big presence in
equity and fixed-income markets. Merrill's revenues from trading on its own
account reached Dollars 396m in the fourth quarter and Dollars 1.9bn in the
year, well up on 1990.
The company singled out its strong performance in trading high-yield
securities and international equities, while trading in money markets,
derivative products (especially swaps), and over-the-counter stocks also
made a significant contribution to trading revenues.
The most spectacular improvement came from investment banking, where
earnings doubled in the last quarter to Dollars 374.8m and rose nearly 50
per cent in the full year to Dollars 1.175bn.
Merrill benefited from a rush of new corporate stock and bond offerings as
companies took advantage of lower interest rates and high stock prices.
For the fourth consecutive year, the company was ranked the leading
underwriter of debt and equity securities both in the US and worldwide.
</TEXT>
