<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JAN 92 / UK News (Employment): NHS accused of sexism over top posts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SEXIST stereotyping about the abilities and 'natural' role of women is
preventing them from being appointed to top health authority jobs, according
to a report published yesterday.
Only one of the UK's 14 regional health authorities is chaired by a woman
and only 16 per cent of district health authorities are chaired by women. Of
the first 57 newly formed National Health Service trusts, only three are
headed by women.
Earlier this month the Department of Health said that all shortlists for
senior NHS management jobs should include female candidates. Targets were
also set for increasing the number of general management posts held by women
from 18 per cent to 30 per cent.
Yesterday's report from the National Association of Health Authorities and
Trusts and the King's Fund Centre is being backed by Mrs Virginia Bottomley,
the health minister.
It found that informal procedures and the 'old boy network' worked against
the selection of women. Suitable women could be found if they were sought
out and government ministers should take the lead and set targets for
regions, said the report.
It pointed out that not only were women primary users of public health
services, they also represented 79 per cent of the NHS's 1.2m employees. The
purpose was not to fill quotas but to obtain a better service for those who
worked in and used the NHS, the report concluded.
It found that Department of Health leaflets used to recruit non-executive
directors could put up barriers. Statements such as 'you must be able to
bring . . . up-to-date specialist knowledge on any number of particular
business areas', or 'you will probably still be at work in industry,
commerce, the public sector or the professions' were seen by the researchers
as restrictive.
Where are the 'good' women? NAHAT, Birmingham Research Park, Vincent Drive,
Birmingham B15 2SQ.
</TEXT>
