<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JAN 92 / Reports of water pollution double
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
REPORTS OF water pollution in England and Wales more than doubled in the
1980s, according to the National Rivers Authority, David Lascelles writes.
The NRA's first compilation of annual statistics yesterday showed that there
were 28,143 reports in 1990, up from 12,600 in 1981. The biggest increase
came in the Northumbria region, where reports rose 57 per cent between 1988
and 1990.
The largest category of reports concerned oil and sewage spills, with each
accounting for just over 20 per cent of the total. Farm incidents accounted
for 11 per cent and industrial incidents 10 per cent.
The NRA pointed out that only a very small proportion of the reported
incidents - 658 in 1990 - could be classed as 'major', involving extensive
fish deaths or the temporary closure of a public water intake.
Dr Jan Pentreath, the NRA chief scientist, said: 'It is important to note
from the figures that the majority of reported incidents are of a minor
nature and that many are not confirmed when investigating officers visit the
scene. On such occasions no legal action can be taken.'
During 1990 the NRA took 282 incidents to court and secured convictions in
272 of them. Dr Pentreath said prosecution was a 'cat-and-mouse game'
because samples had to be collected at the time of the incident, before the
pollution disappeared - and with it the evidence.
</TEXT>
