<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JAN 92 / Fraud office to press for court transcript
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND HUGHES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Serious Fraud Office is to challenge a High Court judge's ruling that it
cannot see the transcript of an examination of Mr Muhammad Naviede, head of
Arrows, the Cheshire-based trade finance company that was compulsorily wound
up in December.
The SFO has charged Mr Naviede with obtaining Pounds 10m by deception from
NMB Postbank, a Dutch company. The criminal proceedings before City of
London magistrates court were adjourned last week until June 15.
The ruling was obtained by the liquidators of Arrows - Mr Scott Martin and
Mr Nigel Hamilton, of Ernst &amp; Young - after they had been granted an order
under section 236 of the Insolvency Act requiring Mr Naviede to attend for
examination.
The liquidators asked the High Court to rule that they would not have to
disclose the transcript of Mr Naviede's evidence to the SFO because they
feared that without such a ruling - the SFO having refused to give an
assurance that it would not seek disclosure - Mr Naviede would not
co-operate with them.
The issue required Mr Justice Hoffmann to consider the apparently
conflicting rights and duties of the SFO under the 1987 Criminal Justice Act
and of liquidators under the Insolvency Act.
He held that the SFO's right to demand information for a fraud investigation
could be restricted by the court to the extent that it was outweighed by an
overriding public interest in secrecy.
Mr Naviede is to seek to have the order for his examination set aside,
raising the privilege against self-incrimination. His application has been
deferred until after the Court of Appeal's judgment on Wednesday on an
appeal by Mr Kevin Maxwell against a High Court decision that he has no
right to silence in proceedings brought under the Insolvency Act.
</TEXT>
