<TEXT>
SHEFFIELD'S steelmaking and engineering companies have asked the government
to cushion the shock of what they say will be 20 per cent increases in
electricity prices from April, Ian Hamilton Fazey writes.
Some say they have experienced 40 per cent rises, and higher costs are
forcing them out of tightening markets.
In an open letter to Mr John Major, the prime minister, manufacturers in a
30-mile radius of Sheffield suggest that the government could relieve
Sheffield's intensive industrial electricity consumers of the fossil fuel
levy.
Professor Stephen Littlechild, the generating industry's regulator, has
criticised some aspects of pricing.
