<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JAN 92 / Executives take on the task of typing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH executives who would have been shocked just a couple of years ago by
the concept of even touching a typewriter are now happily turning out their
own letters and reports.
Nearly 80 per cent of executives and managers currently do at least some of
their typing, according to a survey of over 500 companies published today
Job demarcations between bosses and their secretaries have been eroded
because of the growth in the numbers of personal computers. An estimated 7m
employees now use computers during the working day; the increase in the
number of PCs on managers' desks has been particularly marked, say experts.
Mr Richard Grace, managing director of the Gordon Yates secretarial
recruitment group, which carried out the survey, says the trend in managers
doing typing is going hand in hand with an increase in 'developmental
training' for secretaries. This includes courses in communications skills
and time management.
'As bosses become more computer-literate, they are working in a more
team-based way with their secretaries. It's no longer simply 'take a letter
Miss Jones',' says Mr Grace.
Younger managers are more likely to consider a PC as simply another consumer
durable, according to Mr David Flint, senior consultant with the Butler Cox
Foundation which syndicates information technology research.
The typewriter may have been seen as inconsistent with managerial status;
the computer is an entirely different matter, he adds.
The demarcations between secretaries' and bosses jobs may have been eroded
but differentials between salaries are likely to remain in place. The survey
finds that central London secretarial salaries have increased by an average
of 5.3 per cent over the past year. A junior secretary can expect to earn
about Pounds 10,500 in the capital, while the secretary of a chairman or
chief executive is likely to earn about Pounds 18,600.
Secretarial Salaries in Central London. Gordon Yates, 25 Maddox St, London
W1R OAB. Pounds 12.50
Women's working conditions surveyed, Page 10
Managers 'intimidated', Page 6
</TEXT>
