<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JAN 92 / Labour pledges electoral reform debate: Leadership prepares
to endorse proportional voting for a future Scottish Assembly
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A LABOUR manifesto commit-ment to include the voting system for the House of
Commons in a post-election national debate on electoral reform was
foreshadowed yesterday as the party's leadership prepared to endorse
proportional voting for a Scottish Assembly.
The further shift towards changes in the voting system came as Labour
responded to the third consecutive opinion poll showing a slight
Conservative lead with a new campaign to counter attacks on its tax and
spending policies.
Mr Chris Patten, Tory party chairman, continued to harry the opposition over
the details of its pledges, claiming renewed Labour muddle over the cost of
its immediate commitments. He seized on apparently contradictory comments by
members of the shadow cabinet on the strength of the party's pledge to a
Pounds 1bn economic recovery programme.
Mr Jack Cunningham, Labour's campaign manager and a personal enthusiast for
replacing the 'first-past-the-post' method of electing MPs, suggested wider
debate after the election should involve a constitutional convention or a
Speakers' Conference.
Senior party officials acknowledged pressure on Mr Neil Kinnock to
demonstrate in the manifesto that Labour is ready to consider seriously the
option of radical changes to the electoral system.
In an interview last week with the FT, Mr Kinnock said the constitutional
debate his party had embarked upon was 'a process that will continue into
government.' In spite of the strong opposition of some senior members, a
majority in the shadow cabinet acknowledges the growing momentum behind a
broad manifesto pledge to consider reform.
That momentum will be strengthened when the party's National Executive
Committee is expected broadly to endorse on Wednesday a report from the
committee headed by Professor Raymond Plant of Southampton University which
will recommend that the Scottish Assembly proposed by Labour be elected by
the Additional Member voting system - the hybrid used in Germany to combine
single-member constituencies and regional lists.
Mr Cunningham, speaking on BBC television, dismissed any suggestion that a
new voting system could be part of a post-election deal with the Liberal
Democrats. Many colleagues, however, believe an open-minded approach could
gain the support of a group of floating voters in the south-east. A MORI
survey for the Sunday Times gave the Conservatives a 42 per cent share of
the vote, against 39 per cent for Labour and 16 per cent for the Liberal
Democrats. That followed polls on Saturday which had pointed to a 2-point
and 1-point Tory lead respectively.
Labour said it would respond with a campaign designed to highlight
independent evidence that less than 9 per cent of households would lose, 46
per cent would gain, and 46 per cent would be unaffected by its tax and
benefit proposals.
Row over EC aid Page 6 Monday interview: Tony Blair Page 28
</TEXT>
