<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JAN 92 / Spending on TV advertising shows first flickers of life:
Caution is still the watchword from the industry's executives in spite of an
increase in revenue
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GARY MEAD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IS TELEVISION advertising revenue telling us something the government
desperately wants to hear - that the end of the recession can be spotted in
the distance, drawing slowly closer?
No one in the television world is yet prepared to stick a neck out and
announce even the beginning of the end of a long period of gloom. In a
community more given to razzmatazz than analysis, caution is still the
watchword when it comes to forecasting trends in advertising revenue.
Nevertheless, the last month has seen a considerable uplift in television
advertising revenue. Senior members of the Independent Television
Association point out that the level of advertising expenditure has in the
past often been a useful indicator of which way the UK's overall economy is
headed, and that television advertising is a particularly sensitive
barometer.
Mr Malcolm Wall, chairman of the association's marketing committee and sales
director of Granada TV, said that this January's revenue 'will be up on that
for January 1991 by in excess of 12 per cent, taking us, both ITV and
Channel 4, to some Pounds 114m'. He puts that into perspective - the January
1991 figure was historically low at Pounds 102m, far short of the figure for
the same month in 1989 and 1990, which was Pounds 123m in both years. Mr
Wall said the UK's commercial television networks had 'been badly hit by the
recession, although we had a good final quarter in 1991, up 10 per cent on
one year ago'. He added: 'I expect to see a continued recovery in the first
half of this year, with perhaps 3 per cent to 4 per cent growth in real
terms above the retail prices index.'
That is good news, but hardly begins to catch up with declines, in real
terms, of 5 per cent in 1990 and perhaps 3 per cent in 1991.
According to Mr Peter Battle, sales director of Ulster TV and chairman of
the association's revenue forecasting committee, 'there have been two years
of appalling drops in real terms in an area where there was formerly
unbroken, continuous growth'.
But he also detects a notable uplift in TV advertising revenue in the past
nine months. 'Take 1991: advertising revenue in television was down by 6 per
cent to 9 per cent in the first six months; in the third quarter, down
further by about 1.5 per cent. But the fourth quarter was substantially up,
and there isn't much doubt that the first quarter of 1992 will also be
substantially up.'
Mr Battle says the trend is comforting but should not be exaggerated.
Mr Dominic Proctor, managing director of the UK's largest advertising
agency, J. Walter Thompson, part of the WPP group, also counsels caution.
He said: 'We are forecasting marginal growth, but we are certainly in for
another hard slog this year. The possibility of a double election is a
horror, since companies tend to freeze their spending during an election
period.'
Mr James Best, chairman of the BMP DDB Needham advertising agency, said:
'March will be the real litmus test. Our feeling is that January and
February this year are special cases since those months last year were so
bad. We have some 50 clients, and the mood we have from them is that they
are not prepared to pump-prime the economy but are instead waiting for the
consumer to set the trend. It's too early to put out the flags.'
If the advertising sector overall is still stuck in the doldrums, some
research published tomorrow by Carat, Europe's largest media planning and
buying specialist and part of the Aegis group, seems to confirm that
television is doing rather better.
It indicates that, across Europe as a whole, television advertising revenues
in 1991 showed a real increase of 5.8 per cent, in a year when total media
advertising fell by 0.9 per cent in real terms. Television's share of total
European display advertising reached 33.4 per cent last year, overtaking
newspapers - which in 1991 had 30.4 per cent of the market - for the first
time.
That gap will probably widen over the next two years.
The growth of television advertising, in the UK at least, may be at the cost
of newspapers. The Newspaper Publishers Association has been conducting an
advertising campaign since October designed to persuade advertisers that
print works more effectively than the small screen.
The NPA's campaign has sniped at television, suggesting that viewers pay
scant attention to screened commercials, more to advertisements in print.
According to the latest estimates of the Advertising Association, total
press advertising fell by slightly more than 7 per cent in the first nine
months of 1991. For newspapers there is, as yet, little sign of the sort of
recovery which television is - momentarily - enjoying.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
