<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JAN 92 / Stock Exchange completes regional network
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY, Northern Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE London Stock Exchange has completed a regional network of five offices
which it hopes will improve relations with quoted companies in the Midlands,
the north, Scotland and Northern Ireland.
The process has been completed by the opening of a Leeds office, joining
those in Birmingham, Manchester, Glasgow and Belfast. Leeds and Belfast are
representative offices, while share transfer settlements can be made at the
other three.
The network's completion marks the final transition from the era in which
Britain's largest provincial cities each had its own stock exchange.
The electronic marketplace finally made obsolete the last vestiges of the
local exchanges. The advent of the new Taurus paperless trading system next
year will also end local settlement.
Sir Andrew Hugh Smith, Stock Exchange chairman, said: 'We hope to use our
regional offices to improve relations with listed companies outside London.
In the past we have been a purely regulatory body. We no longer see
ourselves as merely a trade association for stockbrokers.'
Sir Andrew said the new offices would offer commercial services to listed
companies. They would also build contacts with locally based investors and
investment institutions.
The regional offices also run advisory groups of local stockbrokers, who
meet quarterly to hear the opinions of local company chairmen and
commentators. The outcome is then reported to Sir Andrew.
For example, at last week's meeting of the north-west advisory group Mr
Robert Hough, chairman of Manchester Ship Canal, asked for the exchange's
'yellow book' - the rules for quoted companies when reporting potentially
price-sensitive activities - to be made more user-friendly.
The cost of maintaining a Stock Exchange listing was also discussed, as were
the difficulties created for the exchange's marketmakers by the large
numbers of medium-sized or small regional companies whose shares are rarely
traded.
</TEXT>
