<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JAN 92 / UK News (Employment): Powers challenge by Tec chairmen
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE AUTHORITY of the government to block a radical training initiative for
the long-term unemployed, devised by a training and enterprise council, is
to be challenged today.
The challenge to Mr Michael Howard, the employment secretary, will be made
at a meeting of G10, the group of 10 Tec chairmen. It follows the
withholding of approval by Mr Robert Jackson, the employment minister, for a
pilot project planned for this April by Norfolk and Waveney Tec.
The Tec - the chairman of which is Mr John Lineker, recently appointed by
G10 to lead negotiations with the government over funding - sees the case as
an important test of the authority of Tec boards.
Tecs' relations with the government are already strained, with some
threatening not to renew their contracts this year because of proposed cuts
in funding for Youth Training and Employment Training.
Norfolk and Waveney Tec wanted a two-track scheme to replace ET. All the
long-term unemployed would retain their entitlement to training. That could
include short training for those who wanted to brush up on skills to return
to work quickly and longer training for those with special needs.
Those requiring specific occupational skills training could apply for a Tec
'award', for which they would have to demonstrate that they had identified a
need for the relevant skill and a possible job vacancy. Up to 10 per cent of
the award would be paid back in monthly instalments when the individual
found a job.
A letter from Mr Lineker to Mr Howard described the package as 'thoroughly
researched'. It had received overwhelming support from the jobless and
employers.
A letter from Mr Jackson to Mr Lineker said the ideas might be considered
next year.
</TEXT>
