<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JAN 92 / UK News (Employment): Employers warned on job-loss selection
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EMPLOYERS whose redundancy programmes focus on part-time workers may risk a
legal challenge, according to a report by Industrial Relations Services, the
pay research group.
It said a breach of the law might arise because part-time workers were more
likely to be women than men.
Their dismissal might therefore contravene sex discrimination laws.
Industrial Relations Services found in a survey of 120 employers that in the
past two years about a fifth of organisations had altered the way they
decided which employees to dismiss. Most had moved to procedures
concentrating on employee performance.
Some had changed to move away from the principle of last-in-first-out
(Lifo), under which employees with the shortest service are first to go.
Lifo was the main criteria for redundancy selection in less than a third of
the 120 organisations surveyed. The main reason among other companies for
not using it was that it did not allow them to retain their most valued
employees.
Manufacturing companies are more likely to use Lifo than others. Some 38 per
cent of manufacturers used it while the proportion among the rest was 22 per
cent.
About 20 per cent of employers said performance made little difference to
redundancy decisions.
Employment Trends, Industrial Relations Services, 18-20
Highbury Place, London N5 1QP.
Letters, Page 13
</TEXT>
