FT  27 JAN 92 / Campaign launched to save Devonport
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTHONY MORETON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DML, the company that manages Devonport dockyard under contract from the
Ministry of Defence, has launched a campaign to save the dockyard from
closure under the government's Options for Change policy review.
MoD officials say that closure of the dockyard's associated naval base is
ruled out, but that reductions are likely.
Plymouth city council has estimated that closure of the two would cost the
south-west more than Pounds 1bn a year and lead to the loss of some 15,000
jobs in the dockyard, the naval base and the supply industries.
At the centre of the matter is the contest for the contract to refit
nuclear-powered submarines. Devonport handles some 'conventional' nuclear
submarines while refitting work on the Polaris ballistic-missile fleet is
undertaken at Rosyth in Scotland by Babcock Thorn.
Last year the MoD asked the two companies to present proposals for merging
all submarine work at one yard.
The decision has not yet been made, and is thought unlikely before the
election.
There are voices, however, warning the city and company against intensive
lobbying. Dr David Owen, a Plymouth MP, has said that defence decisions will
be taken with national objectives in mind and that pressure lobbying might
be counterproductive.
