<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JAN 92 / House prices expected to fall 2%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HOUSE PRICES are likely to fall by an average of 2 per cent this year
according to a review of the housing market published today.
UBS Phillips &amp; Drew, the firm of stockbrokers, forecasts that prices will
not rise until 1994 even though it expects the number of house sales to rise
by 12 per cent this year.
The firm says that numerous empty, unsold properties on the market will
continue to depress prices even when sales start to recover.
A Financial Times poll last week of estate agents, house builders and
mortgage lenders showed that there had been a sharp increase in interest
from prospective house purchasers since the beginning of the year.
Very few agents and builders felt, however, that the improvement, which
traditionally occurs after Christmas, would lead to a rise in prices.
The UBS study says there were at least 222,000 empty, unsold homes at the
beginning of this year. They included homes repossessed by building
societies, houses and flats which builders had not been able to sell, and a
growing number of inherited homes still seeking purchasers.
UBS expects mortgage lenders to repossess a further 80,000 homes this year.
That is after taking account of the government's 'mortgage-to-rent' rescue
plan, which the study says will apply to about 15,000 homes and 'will have
only a marginal beneficial effect'.
The study cites three factors acting as brakes on the housing market. They
are a more cautious lending policy by building societies and banks, rising
unemployment and concern that a Labour government would increase taxes.
Falling commercial property prices and rents will benefit small businesses,
according to a survey published by National Westminster Bank. The south-east
and south-west are most likely to see an increase in property available,
while the biggest price falls are likely to be in London and the south-west,
the bank says.
Housing Market: Economic Time Bomb. UBS Phillips &amp; Drew, 100 Liverpool St,
London EC2M 2RH. Pounds 95.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 6
