<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JAN 92 / UK plans to open market for international telecoms
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HUGO DIXON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government is close to licensing a new type of international
telecommunications operator which it hopes will undercut prices being
charged on international calls by BT and Mercury Communications.
The new operator could lease cable and satellite capacity in bulk from BT -
previously British Telecom - and Mercury, and sell usage of it to customers.
For example, an operator could lease circuits between London and New York,
and use these to provide a cut-price phone service.
Ministers are unlikely to allow new operators to build and own international
networks.
Sprint, the US telecommunications group, has already applied for a licence.
The moves follow last year's telecommunications white paper which opened the
door to domestic network competition but was vague on international
communications, where BT and Mercury earn their highest rates of
profitability.
The paper said that resale would be allowed on international routes where
the country at the other end had an equivalently open telecommunications
market. No country has yet been considered to be sufficiently liberal.
The Department of Trade and Industry now believes that several countries -
including the US, Japan, Canada, Australia, Sweden and New Zealand - are
likely to pass this test.
Mr John Redwood, the telecommunications minister, has held meetings with US
authorities to try to open up the market. A statement from the US Federal
Communications Commission last month supporting further liberalisation of
the US market is viewed as important by the UK but full clarification is
being sought before resale to the US goes ahead.
The government believes the international network is the part of the market
where prices are most out of line with costs. Observers argue that, although
resale will exert some downward pressure on prices, the full benefits will
only come from network competition.
But the government is concerned that a unilateral opening of the UK market
could put British companies at a disadvantage unless foreign markets were
also opened up. It also fears that foreign telephone companies could abuse
their power in overseas markets to distort competition in the UK, if they
were granted international licences.
Ministers would have had to address similar concerns if American Telephone
and Telegraph, the largest US telecommunications operator, were to take a
stake in Mercury.
The government would consider using its 'golden' share in Cable and
Wireless, Mercury's parent, to ensure that any tie-up did not lead to a
distortion of the market.
