FT  27 JAN 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Terry Wogan continues his bid for heavyweight status by wandering among a
studio full of young people (that's right, just like Kilroy) and urging them
to ask questions of a panel of Liberal Democrats in Wogan (7.00). Last week
he did Labour, next week, presumably, the Tories.
People who burn poundsworths' of petrol in their Volvo Estates taking little
packets of newspapers to the recycling dump do not thank you when you tell
them that most of the paper ostensibly collected for recycling in Britain is
actually used for landfill. (Fact). They will probably be deeply upset by
tonight's Horizon which, instead of blithely accepting the sentimental
middle class view that Red Indians are the original environmentalists and
the guardians of mother earth, sets out to check whether this is true (8.10
BBC2).
There is a three-way choice at 9.00. ITV starts another run of El Cid, the
tale of cops and robbers on the Costa Brava, now minus Alfred Molina. BBC2
screens Arena on the 50th anniversary of 'Desert Island Discs'.
And, my choice, C4 shows the third of an excellent four-part documentary on
The Falklands War.
</TEXT>
