<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JAN 92 / Campaign launched to save Devonport
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTHONY MORETON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DML, THE privately owned company that manages Devonport dockyard under
contract from the Ministry of Defence, has launched a campaign to save the
dockyard from closure.
Mr Mike Leece, managing director, has warned the 5,000 workforce 'there is a
real possibility that the Devonport dockyard could close'.
He is supported in the campaign by Mr John Ingham, Labour leader of Plymouth
City Council, who has said that 'Devonport can stand the strictest
comparison with Britain's other naval facilities. It fully deserves to
flourish'.
If the dockyard were to close under the ministry's Options for Change policy
review, it might lead to serious doubts over the future of the associated
naval base itself, which employs some 4,700 people. MoD officials say that
closure of the base is ruled out, but that reductions are likely.
The city council has estimated that closure of the two would cost the
south-west of England more than Pounds 1bn a year directly and indirectly
and lead to the loss of some 15,000 jobs in the dockyard, the naval base and
the supply industries.
'We are fighting for the survival not just of the dockyard but for Plymouth
and the whole south-west,' Mr Leece said.
At thecentre of the matter is the contest for the contract to refit
nuclear-powered submarines. Under present arrangements, Devonport handles
some 'conventional' nuclear submarines while refitting work on the Polaris
ballistic-missile fleet is undertaken at Rosyth in Scotland by Babcock
Thorn.
Last year the MoD, as part of Options for Change, asked the two companies to
present proposals for merging all submarine work at one yard.
The ministry has been holding the two reports since last November and there
are fears in Plymouth that after the outcry over the closure of the
Ravenscraig steel works in Lanarkshire the government will throw Scotland a
bone before the election and place all its submarine work in Rosyth. The
decision on whether to concentrate all the nuclear submarine work at a
single site has not yet been made, and is thought unlikely before the
election.
A report commissioned by Plymouth City Council from Mr Eric Grove, an
independent consultant, concluded that 'Devonport offers the greatest
efficiency and scope for growth of all the naval base/dockyard complexes'.
There are voices, however, warning the city and company against intensive
lobbying. Dr David Owen, a Plymouth MP, has said that defence decisions will
be taken with national objectives in mind and that pressure lobbying might
be counterproductive.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
