<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JAN 92 / Halifax will charge on low funds
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SCHEHERAZADE DANESHKHU
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HALIFAX, Britain's largest building society, confirmed yesterday that it is
to impose charges on February 1 on customers with low balances in their
savings accounts, but said its decision was fair to most of its customers.
The society, which made pre-tax profits of Pounds 593m last year, said its
margin on interest earned from mortgage-lending and interest paid to its
3.6m savers was being squeezed.
Customers with balances of less than Pounds 250 can have two free
withdrawals a month, but will have to pay 60p for further cash withdrawals
and Pounds 1 for cheques.
People with balances of less than Pounds 50 for 30 days or more in each
quarter will also have to pay a quarterly charge of Pounds 2.50. Account
holders aged 21 or below are exempt.
Halifax said low-balance savings accounts used frequently were run at a
loss.
Abbey National, one of Halifax's main rivals, said it had no plans to make a
similar move.
Finance and the Family, Weekend Page II
</TEXT>
